lock() blocks until the mutex becomes available, which can reduce responsiveness if the lock is held for a long time. 
try_lock() avoids blocking by immediately returning true if the lock is acquired or false if it is not, 
allowing the thread to perform other work instead of waiting.lock() is a blocking call.

If another thread already owns the mutex, the calling thread waits indefinitely until the mutex becomes available.

Why use try_lock()?

try_lock() is non-blocking.

If the mutex is busy, it immediately returns false, allowing the thread to continue doing other work.

********************Real-Life Example

Suppose two threads want to write to a log file.

Using lock()
Thread 1
Writes log...

Thread 2
Waits...
Waits...
Waits...

Thread 2 is blocked until Thread 1 finishes.

Using try_lock()
Thread 1
Writes log...

Thread 2
Could not get lock.
Continues processing other work.

The application stays responsive because Thread 2 doesn't waste time waiting.

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>

using namespace std;

mutex m;

void task(int id)
{
    if (m.try_lock())
    {
        cout << "Thread " << id << " acquired the lock\n";

        this_thread::sleep_for(chrono::seconds(2));

        cout << "Thread " << id << " releasing the lock\n";

        m.unlock();
    }
    else
    {
        cout << "Thread " << id << " could not acquire the lock\n";
    }
}

int main()
{
    thread t1(task, 1);
    thread t2(task, 2);

    t1.join();
    t2.join();

    return 0;
}

Few points to remember about try_lock():

1. try_lock() attempts to lock the mutex and returns immediately.
   • Returns true if the lock is acquired.
   • Returns false if the mutex is already locked.

2. try_lock() is a non-blocking operation.
   If the mutex is unavailable, the calling thread does NOT wait.

3. If try_lock() succeeds, the thread must eventually call unlock().

4. If try_lock() fails, do NOT call unlock().

5. Calling try_lock() again on the same std::mutex from the thread
   that already owns it results in undefined behavior.
   (std::mutex is non-recursive.)

6. If you need the same thread to lock the mutex multiple times,
   use std::recursive_mutex instead.

